Root Volumes

Definition:

The root volume is the primary disk attached to a system that contains the operating system (OS) and boot files.
It is required for the instance to boot.

Characteristics: 

Usually mounted at / (root directory)
Automatically attached when the instance is launched
Typically has the OS pre-installed in cloud images (AMI in AWS)

-------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Data Volumes

Definition:

Data volumes are additional disks attached to an instance for storing user data, application data, databases, logs, etc.
They are not required for booting and can be attached or detached dynamically.

Characteristics:

Mounted anywhere (e.g., /mnt/data1)
Can be standalone disks (physical volumes) or used in LVM for logical volumes
Can be added, removed, resized, or moved across instances

-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

naming:

Root volume   →   system disk, required to boot (/dev/xvda, /dev/xvdb. /dev/xvdc, etc)
Data volumes  →   additional storage, flexible, attachable/detachable (/dev/xvdf, /dev/xvdg, /dev/xvdh, etc)
